```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string filename = "input.txt";
    std::string target_word = "apple";
    std::string line;
    size_t count = 0;

    std::ifstream file(filename);

    if (file.is_open()) {
        while (getline(file, line)) {
            size_t pos = 0;
            while ((pos = line.find(target_word, pos)) != std::string::npos) {
                count++;
                pos += target_word.length();
            }
        }
        file.close();

        std::cout << "The word 'apple' occurs " << count << " times in the file.\n";
    } else {
        std::cerr << "Unable to open file: " << filename << '\n';
    }

    return 0;
}
```

This program reads the file line by line using `getline()`, searches for occurrences of the target word within each line using `find()`, and keeps a count. If the file cannot be opened, an error message is displayed. Make sure to replace "input.txt" with the path to your actual text file.

Keep in mind that this example is case-sensitive, so it will only count occurrences of the target word if it appears exactly as given (in lowercase "apple" in this case). If you want case-insensitive searching, you can convert both the line and target_word to lowercase before comparing.

